07584nam a22018495i 9780691240244DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212007nju    fo  d z      eng d  a9780691240244  a(DE-B1597)613943  a(OCoLC)1291506946  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aART0150602bisacsh04a700.9372221 aElsner, Jaś, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRoman Eyes :bVisuality and Subjectivity in Art and Text /cJaś Elsner. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (376 p.) :b16 color plates. 88 halftones.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tPrologue -- t1 Between Mimesis and Divine Power Visuality in the Greco-Roman World -- tPart 1 Ancient Discourses of Art -- t2. Image and Ritual Pausanias and the Sacred Culture of Greek Art -- t3. Discourses of Style Connoisseurship in Pausanias and Lucian -- t4. Ekphrasis and the Gaze From Roman Poetry to Domestic Wall Painting -- tPart 2 Ways of Viewing -- t5. Viewing and Creativity Ovid’s Pygmalion as Viewer -- t6. Viewer as Image Intimations of Narcissus -- t7. Viewing and Decadence Petronius’ Picture Gallery -- t8. Genders of Viewing Visualizing Woman in the Casket of Projecta -- t9. Viewing the Gods The Origins of the Icon in the Visual Culture of the Roman East -- t10. Viewing and Resistance Art and Religion in Dura Europos -- tEpilogue From Diana via Venus to Isis Viewing the Deity with Apuleius -- tBibliography -- tIndex Locorum -- tGeneral Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Roman Eyes, Jas Elsner seeks to understand the multiple ways that art in ancient Rome formulated the very conditions for its own viewing, and as a result was complicit in the construction of subjectivity in the Roman Empire. Elsner draws upon a wide variety of visual material, from sculpture and wall paintings to coins and terra-cotta statuettes. He examines the different contexts in which images were used, from the religious to the voyeuristic, from the domestic to the subversive. He reads images alongside and against the rich literary tradition of the Greco-Roman world, including travel writing, prose fiction, satire, poetry, mythology, and pilgrimage accounts. The astonishing picture that emerges reveals the mindsets Romans had when they viewed art--their preoccupations and theories, their cultural biases and loosely held beliefs. Roman Eyes is not a history of official public art--the monumental sculptures, arches, and buildings we typically associate with ancient Rome, and that tend to dominate the field. Rather, Elsner looks at smaller objects used or displayed in private settings and closed religious rituals, including tapestries, ivories, altars, jewelry, and even silverware. In many cases, he focuses on works of art that no longer exist, providing a rare window into the aesthetic and religious lives of the ancient Romans.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAesthetics, Roman. 0aArts, Classical. 0aVisual perception. 7aART / History / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAdoration.  aAelius Aristides.  aAeschylus.  aAgalmatophilia.  aAnchises.  aAncient Greek art.  aAncient Rome.  aAnecdote.  aAnthropomorphism.  aApuleius.  aArt history.  aAtargatis.  aBathing.  aBibliography.  aCapitoline Museums.  aCastration.  aChristian apologetics.  aConflation.  aCooling.  aCult image.  aCupid and Psyche.  aDe Dea Syria.  aDeity.  aDiana and Actaeon.  aDrapery.  aEkphrasis.  aEpigram.  aEpithet.  aEroticism.  aGenre.  aGreco-Roman world.  aH II region.  aHagiography.  aHare Krishna (mantra).  aHarpocrates.  aHe